class SeatManager {
public:
    SeatManager(int n) {
        seats = new vector<int>(n, 0);
        lastAvailable = 1;
    }

    int reserve() {
        int seat = lastAvailable;
        seats[seat - 1] = seat;
        lastAvailable++;
        return seat;
    }

    void unreserve(int seatNumber) {
        seats[seatNumber - 1] = lastAvailable;
        lastAvailable--;
    }
private:
    vector<int>* seats;
    int lastAvailable;
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: We use a vector to store the seat numbers and a pointer to keep track of the last available seat. The reserve function returns the last available seat and updates the last available seat. The unreserve function updates the last available seat when a seat is unreserved. The time complexity is O(1) because we only access and update a constant number of elements in the vector.

